# Code Commenting Rules

## Documentation Comments

### File Header Comments
Every file MUST start with a JSDoc-style header comment:

```javascript
/**
 * @version 0.0.1
 * Updated On : [Date]
 * Brief description of the file's purpose
 */
```

### Function Documentation
Document all exported functions and complex functions:

```javascript
/**
 * Function description
 * @param {Type} paramName - Parameter description
 * @param {Type} paramName2 - Parameter description (optional)
 * @returns {Type} Return value description
 */
export const functionName = (paramName, paramName2 = defaultValue) => {
  // Implementation
};
```

### API Function Documentation
API functions MUST include detailed JSDoc:

```javascript
/**
 * Login API
 * @param data - Login credentials
 * @param toast_success - Success message if provided. Default value false.
 * @param toast_loading - Loading message if provided. Default value false.
 * @returns JSON response or null.
 */
Login: (data, toast_success = false, toast_loading = false) => {
  // Implementation
}
```

## Inline Comments

### Section Dividers
Use clear section dividers for code organization:

```javascript
//-------------------Section Title-------------------//

//-------------- State & Variables --------------//

//----------------- API Calls --------------//

//-------------- Event Handlers --------------//
```

### Complex Logic
Add comments for non-obvious logic:

```javascript
// Handle concurrent refresh attempts
if (isRefreshing) {
  // Queue the request to retry after token refresh
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    failedQueue.push({ resolve, reject });
  });
}
```

### TODO Comments
Use TODO comments for future improvements:

```javascript
// TODO: In production, send to error tracking service (e.g., Sentry)
// if (errorTrackingService) {
//   errorTrackingService.captureException(...args);
// }
```

## Comment Guidelines

### DO Comment
- File purposes and responsibilities
- Complex algorithms or business logic
- API endpoints and their parameters
- Non-obvious code decisions
- Workarounds or temporary solutions
- Public APIs and exported functions

### DON'T Comment
- Self-explanatory code
- Obvious variable names
- Simple getters/setters
- Standard React patterns (unless non-standard)

## Version Tracking
- Update `@version` when making significant changes
- Update `Updated On` date when modifying files
- Use semantic versioning: `0.0.1`, `0.0.2`, etc.

## Code Organization Comments
Use section comments to organize component code:

```javascript
const Component = () => {
  //-------------- State & Variables --------------//
  const [state, setState] = useState();
  
  //-------------- Hooks --------------//
  const dispatch = useAppDispatch();
  
  //-------------- Effects --------------//
  useEffect(() => {
    // Effect logic
  }, []);
  
  //-------------- Event Handlers --------------//
  const handleClick = () => {
    // Handler logic
  };
  
  //-------------- Render --------------//
  return <div>...</div>;
};
```
